<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n28068a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n28" href="#n28068a">N28 (VI.D.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n28all.htm#n28068a"> 68(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> W&apos;s statue robed in red</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Other processions not popular with the vast mass of the population were those which made a circuit on the 12th of July and 4th of November, the anniversaries of the Battle of the Boyne and the birthday of King <mark>William</mark>, around the equestrian <mark>statue</mark> of his Majesty in College Green; the effigy on such occasions being <mark>dressed in a flaming cloak and sash</mark>, and decorated with orange lilies, the horse made splendid with ribbons of the same colour, whilst beneath his upraised foot were ribbons of the national colour, on which he was ready to trample. <small> J. Fitzgerald Molloy, <a name="JFMR1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JFMR1"><cite title="source">The Romance of the Irish Stage</cite></a> (1897) I 58f</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c11163a" href="c11all.htm#c11163a">VI.C.11:163(a)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
